{
  "text": "Figures 4a-g show all three IPF's (N, L, and T) representing the U-10Mo fuel texture as a function of the processing step. In contrast to the Zr layer, considerable texture evolution is evident in the U-10Mo foil with each successive processing step. Following hot-rolling, a typical bcc rolling texture is evident, with (110) poles aligned with the rolling direction and (111) poles along the foil normal [CITATION_1] . The texture is weakened somewhat, from a peak of 5.2 MRD to 4.0 MRD following the PHR anneal at 923K for 45 minutes. Cold-rolling to 20% or 50% once again increases the strength of the texture to a peak of 4.4 MRD. In contrast to the PHR anneal, the PCR anneal at 923K for 60 minutes almost completely randomizes the texture. Indeed, following the higher temperature anneals at 1023K and 1123K, a distinct texture component develops with the (100) poles aligned with the rolling direction.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "18572721"
